Congratulations to Atlantis Charter High School‚Äôs Class of 2020!

The Atlantis Charter School Class of 2020 said a final farewell Wednesday to their classmates as they looked forward to college and careers.

Delayed due to COVID-19 limits on gatherings, a socially distanced graduation ceremony was held for the 58 graduating students on the school grounds Wednesday evening. In an interview Thursday morning, Gabriela Birmingham, kindergarten through Grade 12 district director, expressed her pride in the Class of 2020 and said the school was happy to be able to hold a graduation so the students could celebrate this milestone in their lives with their parents.

Featured on NBC 10 WJAR!

Two health and physical education teachers from Atlantis Charter School biked over 140 miles total over a span of eight days to visit with all of their students at a safe distance.

We said, "We need to go visit our students to make sure they're socially, emotionally, and physically OK", and so we said, "Let's go take a bike ride and see them", said Bethany Daniels, one of the two PE teachers.

Watch and read more here: https://turnto10.com/news/coronavirus/show-us-something-good/two-physical-education-teachers-bike-140-miles-to-socially-distance-visit-with-students

post_text: Beginning tomorrow, Tuesday, March 17th, Atlantis is offering a ‚ÄúGrab N‚Äô Go‚Äù meal program for all Atlantis students. Meal pick up is available at the school‚Äôs 37 Park Street administrative building (next to St. Anne‚Äôs Church and across from Kennedy Park). *There are no meals being offered at the school building on Jefferson Street.* The program takes place each weekday from 11:30am to 12:30pm, and students will receive a lunch for that day and a breakfast for the following morning. post_text:
From ACS Athletics!

In Sports News:

Last night the Girls Varsity Basketball team won its second game in a row, with a decisive victory over Avon High School 55-28.

The Tritons were led by Tanea Jackson with her great work in the paint, scoring 21 points. Synthia Comas finished with 13 pts, and Aaliyah Ramos added 7 more points.

The entire team played great defense.

The Tritons are now 2-1 on the season and are off until the new year (1/7/20 @ Avon HS)

There are two Basketball Games today. The Boys JV team is playing at 4:00pm, and the Boys Varsity follows with their game at 5:30pm. Both games are against Coyle Cassidy. $2 Adults, $1 for students, seniors, and children over 12.

post_text:
From ACS Athletics

This past Monday night the Girls Varsity basketball team traveled to face Sturgis West High School. The contest between the two teams was close for most of the game, but the Tritons prevailed 25-23, as Aaliyah Ramos hit two free throws with ten seconds left to secure the victory. This was the team‚Äôs first victory of the season.

Top scorers for the game included: Sidney Bednarz (8), Tanea Jackson (7), and Aaliyah Ramos (7). Sidney Bednarz also had 4 steals in the game as part of a stingy Tritons defense.

The team is now 1-1 on the season. Their next game is Wednesday 12/18/2019 at home vs. Avon 4pm.

GO TRITONS!

Our Atlantis Charter Tritons will face off against Cohasset High School at Holbrook High School at 5:00pm.

post_text:
Atlantis Charter won its South Sectional semi-final game over Cape Cod Tech 5-1.

Atlantis scored ten minutes in. Luis Flores score the first goal. Half way through the first half Andre Filho-Coelho scored the second goal, both goals were assisted by Ronaldo Ribeiro.

Right before the first half Mayson Branco scored, assisted by David Duarte.

In the second half the Tritons score to quick goals, both by Ronaldo Ribeiro, assisted by Andre Filho-Coelho and David Duarte.

Cape Cod scored half way through the second half, but the Tritons went into defensive mode and Cape Cod Tech never got another shot off.

The Tritons have advanced to the South Sectional Finals to face the winner of Cohasset vs Carver. The game will be played on Saturday Nov 16th at 6:30pm.

post_text:
Our students are having fun with #STEM all this week during #MassSTEMWeek! Students in Mr. Buck's 9th grade physics class are learning about Newton's Second Law of Motion which states that the acceleration of an object is dependent on two variables - the net force acting upon the object and the mass of an object.

Mr. Buck modeled this through an activity in the hallway which involved various forces pushing on students (and administrator) in a rolling chair in the hallway to see impact on acceleration. Mrs. Birmingham "rolled" with it for this activity! #SeeYourselfInSTEM #EdThatAddsUp

FAQ! Who can enroll at Atlantis?

Enrollment is open to children of the Commonwealth with priority given to children who reside in Fall River. Proof of residency shall include any one of the following: a valid driver‚Äôs license or a voter registration card and a current utility bill or rent receipt. All applications must have a valid Massachusetts address listed as their permanent residence, and to which all communication will be mailed, to be eligible for the lottery.
